          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Overview</span>
              <h2>What Are Government Bonds?</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Government bonds, commonly known as Government Securities (G-Sec), are debt instruments issued by the Government of India to finance its fiscal deficit and public expenditure. These bonds carry a sovereign guarantee, meaning the government pledges to repay the principal and interest, making them virtually risk-free investments.</p>
            <p>The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) conducts auctions of government securities on behalf of the central government. Through the RBI Retail Direct scheme launched in 2021, individual investors can now directly participate in primary auctions and buy G-Secs with a minimum investment of just ₹10,000, without needing a broker or intermediary.</p>
            <p>G-Secs come in various forms including fixed-rate bonds, floating-rate bonds, and inflation-indexed bonds. With tenures ranging from 91 days (Treasury Bills) to 40 years, they cater to investors with different time horizons. The predictable nature of government bond returns makes them the benchmark against which all other fixed-income investments are measured.</p>
          </div>

