  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Government Bonds</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can I buy government bonds directly from RBI?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, through the RBI Retail Direct scheme, individual investors can open a free Retail Direct Gilt (RDG) account and directly participate in primary auctions of Government Securities, Treasury Bills, and Sovereign Gold Bonds. The minimum investment is ₹10,000 and there are no brokerage or account maintenance charges.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between Treasury Bills and G-Secs?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Treasury Bills (T-Bills) are short-term instruments with tenures of 91, 182, or 364 days. They don't pay periodic interest — instead, they're issued at a discount and redeemed at face value. Dated Government Securities (G-Secs) have longer tenures (5-40 years) and pay semi-annual coupon interest. Both carry sovereign guarantee.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is interest from government bonds taxable?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, interest earned from government bonds is fully taxable and added to your total income at your applicable slab rate. However, no TDS is deducted at source on G-Sec interest. Capital gains from selling before maturity are taxed as short-term (slab rate) if held less than 12 months, or long-term (12.5% after indexation) if held longer.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the risk of investing in government bonds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>While government bonds have zero credit risk (sovereign guarantee), they carry interest rate risk. If interest rates rise after you buy a bond, its market value will fall. This matters only if you sell before maturity — if you hold to maturity, you receive the full face value. Longer-tenure bonds have higher interest rate sensitivity. Inflation risk is another factor, as real returns may erode if inflation exceeds the coupon rate.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How does the RBI Floating Rate Bond work?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>The RBI Floating Rate Savings Bond 2020 (Taxable) offers an interest rate that resets every 6 months, linked to the prevailing NSC rate plus a 35 basis point spread. Currently yielding 8.05%, it provides protection against interest rate changes. The tenure is 7 years with no premature withdrawal (except for senior citizens after specific periods). It can be purchased from designated banks.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

